<Author>jaykayess
<Content>Novotel Citygate: Good hotel; Superb location My wife and I stayed at the Novotel Citygate, Hong Kong, for 3 nights in October 2008. We'd been planning a getaway to Hing Kong for some time, and had researched all the hotel reviews here on tripAdvisor before making our choice.We picked this hotel for three reasons:1. Excellent reviews2. They accepted American Express reward point vouchers (which is what I used to pay for my room, so it was essentially free)3. LocationWe were extremely happy with our choice and had an excellent stay overall. Let me clarify that I cannot comment on value for money, since I used reward points, and did not pay for the room at all.Our good experience started with the reservation process way back in July. They told us that there was no availability for the dates we wanted. But I sent a simple e-mail requesting them to reconsider, as it was a special ocassion for us. Within a couple of days, they got back to us with a confirmed reservation.I must mention that there are many hotels who do not like to accomodate non-paying guests like us who use vouchers. But despite knowing that we were using vouchers, they gave us a confirmation, which I interpret as a very positive customer attitude.The second good experience was with the free airport transfer. (The hotel is situated hardly 10-15 minutes drive from Lap Chek Kok airport.) Novotel has their own shuttle bus running every 15 minutes, and we had no trouble at all in finding the shuttle desk on arrival at the airport, and were promptly and efficiently transported to the hotel.Check-in smooth (even with our vouchers), but the only hitch was that since our flight had landed at 9.15 a.m, we were in the hotel by 10 a.m., but they told us that our room would only be ready at noon. So after a 6-hour flight from Bombay, we had to kill a couple of hours in the attached mall (more on that below). I found the front desk guy to be a bit rigid on this, and got some irritated vibes from him, but didn't bother pushing too hard as we wanted our holiday to be a totally relaxing experience and starting off with an argument was not a good way to do that.The room was ready by the time we sauntered back at around 12.30 pm. It seems to be a very new hotel, because everything looked and felt new in the room, and that's always nice. I've stayed in many hotels that are luxurious but old, and even though they were spotlessly maintained, nothing beats the feel of a new room. In fact, because of this, we could overlook the fact that the room was actually quite small - much smaller than the visual impression you get from seeing the pictures on their website.Everything in our 11th floor room worked as it should: Air-conditioning, TV, shower (hand-shower plus a rain shower - no bathtub), room lighting, etc. The room was very quiet and we did not even hear any noise from the aircraft taking off from the airport, which we could see from the window. We also had a pretty good view of a little garden of a nearby apartment complex, and the rest of the view was wide open and green - not rural, but not at all what you would expect in a megapolis and one of the world's most densely populated cities.Now about the location: For us, this was an absolute highlight of our stay.First of all, Lantau island is completely different from Hong Kong island or the mainland (Kowloon), because it's not crowded or over-developed.Next, the hotel itself is contiguous with one of the largest malls in Hong Kong - the Citygate outlet mall. All you do is take an escalator from the lobby and you're in the mall. Bliss!!Third, the mall has an MTR station right inside it (Tung Chung station). So you are connected into the system effortlessly and don't ever have to step out to take a bus or taxi. We bought Octopus pre-paid cards on the first day and went everywhere using the MTR - Hong kong, Kowloon, the bus to Po-Ling... Extremely convenient, clean, safe, fast, comfortable and hassle-free. Works well for 1 or 2 people (taxi may trun out cheaper for a family of 4). It took us 20-25 minutes by MRT to reach Hong Kong Central.Finally, the location was very convenient to us for sightseeing. One of the attractions that we were interested in was the giant Buddha statue near Po Lin monastery. If we'd been living in a hotel in Hong Kong or Kowloon, we'd have had to take the MTR to Tung Ching station to go there. But guess what - we were already there! (We didn't know about this when we made our reservation). All we had to do was take the cable car or bus from outside the mall to go up to the monastery and statue.Incidentally, for those interested in visiting ong Kong Disneyland, Tung Chung station is just one MRT stop away from the stop for Disneyland.FOOD: We are strict vegetarians and were aware that we have very limited choices. Also, since we were not paying for the rooms, breakfst was not included in our vouchers.We did not eat at any of the hotel restaurants, or order anything from room service at all. We normally depend on four sources of food: (a) International fast food chains with known menus/ingredients (e.g. Pizza Hut) (b) Carrying some of our own dry/packaged food from home (c) local Indian restaurants and (d) buying ingredients from supermarkets if we have access to basic cooking facilities.In this case, it was a mix of the first three. There is ample choice of restaurants in Citygate mall. Also, there is a fully stocked supermarket on the ground floor of the mall. And there are quite a few Indian restaurants on Hong Kong island. For breakfast, we picked up cereal, bread and juice for breakfast from the supermarket and ate in the room. The hotel staff was very helpful in providing cutlery and crockery every morning. Tea and coffee were also available as part of the room amenities.For check-out, we requested a two-hour extension, i.e., 2 pm instead of 12 noon. But again, the front desk guy very firmly refused, saying they were full and could not accomodate us. It was quite apparent from the vast empty lobby that they were not really anywhere near full!I again sensed an unwillingness on his part to even try - he just shook his head and said no. Not rude or anytthing, but completely unshakeable and unapologetic about it. Maybe it had something to do with the fact that we were paying with vouchers...???But anyway, he let us leave our bags at the concierge, and we could do some last day shopping in the mall and then take the 4 pm free shuttle to the airport.So overall, an excellent stay. I've taken off one star only for their unwillingness to help us with early check-in / late check-out.I'd strongly recommend this hotel to anyone who wants a peaceful stay near Hong kong without being in the midst of the crowded city and yet with quick and convenient access to the districts of Central, Wan Chai, Kowloon, or anywhere on the MRT network. 
